  "text": "The concept of ID is firstly introduced in one of our previous work [CITATION_1] . As far as a rule is concerned, its Rule-ID is defined as a P-bit ternary ('1','0', or '*') bit-string, each bit of which is extracted from certain bit position within the rule's matching condition. Accordingly, the term Key-ID is defined as the P binary bits ('1'or '0') extracted from the corresponding bit positions within a given key. For example, suppose P=2, and the 2 bit positions are SIP(16) and PROT [CITATION_2] . Then the Rule-ID of rule <1.1.*.*, 2.*.*.*, *, *, 6> is\"*0\"and the Key-ID of search key <1.1.1.1, 2.2.2.2, 1028, 34556, 11> is\"01\".",
